    },
    "is_accepted" : true,
    "score" : 1909,
    "last_activity_date" : 1516743208,
    "last_edit_date" : 1516743208,
    "creation_date" : 1264997353,
    "answer_id" : 2174607,
    "question_id" : 860187,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>There's another solution that also works.  </p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Go to the <em>Build Path</em> settings in the project properties.</li>\n<li>Remove the <em>JRE System Library</em></li>\n<li>Add it back; Select <em>\"Add Library\"</em> and select the <em>JRE System Library</em>. The default worked for me.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>This works because you have multiple classes in different jar files. Removing and re-adding the JRE lib will make the right classes be first.\nIf you want a fundamental solution make sure you exclude the jar files with the same classes.</p>\n\n<p>For me I have: <code>javax.xml.soap.SOAPPart</code> in three different jars: <code>axis-saaj-1.4.jar</code>, <code>saaj-api-1.3.jar</code> and the <code>rt.jar</code></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 604571,
      "reputation" : 151,
      "user_id" : 306307,
      "user_type" : "unregistered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4f93a23548883527a8ff5b03d6bd412e?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Mayur",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/306307/mayur"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 15,
    "last_activity_date" : 1279142800,
    "last_edit_date" : 1279142800,
    "creation_date" : 1270062588,
    "answer_id" : 2555768,
    "question_id" : 860187,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<ul>\n<li>Go to the Build Path settings in the project properties.\n<code>Windows -&gt; Preferences -&gt; Java Compiler</code></li>\n<li>Remove the JRE System Library</li>\n<li>Add another JRE with a \"perfect match\"</li>\n<li>clean and build your project again. It worked for me.</li>\n</ul>\n"
  }, {
