    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 14,
    "last_activity_date" : 1309513570,
    "creation_date" : 1309513570,
    "answer_id" : 6546307,
    "question_id" : 860187,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I just had this problem too. Apparently I had set the JRE to 1.5 instead of 1.6 in my build path.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 57055,
      "reputation" : 5707,
      "user_id" : 170918,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/588ff0dd4dadbda1a60f0b40a21cf2b9?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Mr. Napik",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/170918/mr-napik"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 6,
    "last_activity_date" : 1364829497,
    "creation_date" : 1364829497,
    "answer_id" : 15746118,
    "question_id" : 860187,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In the case you are sure that you should be able to access given class, than this can mean you added several jars to your project containing classes with identical names (or paths) but different content and they are overshadowing each other (typically an old custom build jar contains built-in older version of a 3rd party library).</p>\n\n<p>For example when you add a jar implementing:</p>\n\n<pre><code>a.b.c.d1\na.b.c.d2\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>but also an older version implementing only:</p>\n\n<pre><code>a.b.c.d1\n(d2 is missing altogether or has restricted access)\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Everything works fine in the code editor but fails during the compilation if the \"old\" library overshadows the new one - d2 suddenly turns out \"missing or inaccessible\" even when it is there.</p>\n\n<p>The solution is a to check the order of compile-time libraries and make sure that the one with correct implementation goes first.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 2268229,
        "reputation" : 1620,
        "user_id" : 1996306,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 100,
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/82R7o.png?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Steven",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1996306/steven"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1372304795,
      "post_id" : 16733303,
      "comment_id" : 25146559,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "Fair enough, but you&#39;ve basically replicated the wording of the accepted answer by Nels Beckman."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1668716,
      "reputation" : 2619,
      "user_id" : 1535606,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 21,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dd206533e38e8238c682af3dc4a49b4b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Arun Chandrasekaran",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1535606/arun-chandrasekaran"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 7,
    "last_activity_date" : 1369392706,
    "creation_date" : 1369392706,
    "answer_id" : 16733303,
    "question_id" : 860187,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Sorry for updating an old POST. I got the reported problem and I solved it as said below.</p>\n\n<p>Assuming you are using Eclipse + m2e maven plugin, if you get this access restriction error, right click on the project/module in which you have the error --> Properties --> Build Path --> Library --> Replace JDK/JRE to the one that is used in eclipse workspace.</p>\n\n<p>I followed the above steps and the issue is resolved.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 373119,
      "reputation" : 3603,
      "user_id" : 722553,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/523abb68d12ba47b086c100b203b25f1?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Dawngerpony",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/722553/dawngerpony"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 29,
    "last_activity_date" : 1378470710,
    "creation_date" : 1378470710,
    "answer_id" : 18657966,
    "question_id" : 860187,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I have been getting this error too, but my project is built on the command line using Maven and the <a href=\"http://eclipse.org/tycho/\">tycho</a> compiler (it's a set of OSGi plugins). After masses of sifting through people having the same problem but fixing it in Eclipse rather than on the command line, I found <a href=\"http://dev.eclipse.org/mhonarc/lists/tycho-user/msg03670.html\">a message on the Tycho developer forum</a> that answered my question, using configuration in <code>pom.xml</code> to ignore the compiler warning about the access restriction:</p>\n\n<pre><code>&lt;plugin&gt;\n    &lt;groupId&gt;org.eclipse.tycho&lt;/groupId&gt;\n    &lt;artifactId&gt;tycho-compiler-plugin&lt;/artifactId&gt;\n    &lt;version&gt;${tycho.version}&lt;/version&gt;\n    &lt;configuration&gt;\n        &lt;compilerArgument&gt;-warn:+discouraged,forbidden&lt;/compilerArgument&gt;\n    &lt;/configuration&gt;\n&lt;/plugin&gt;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>More information can be found in the <a href=\"http://wiki.eclipse.org/Tycho/FAQ\">Tycho FAQ</a>. This took me AGES to work out, so I figured I would assist anyone else trying to fix these access restriction errors from the command line by posting this answer.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1831332,
      "reputation" : 1350,
      "user_id" : 1662668,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 78,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dc27056a9f493abc36b3efcd2beb2461?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Soumyajit Swain",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1662668/soumyajit-swain"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1471338261,
    "last_edit_date" : 1471338261,
    "creation_date" : 1395208770,
    "answer_id" : 22497515,
    "question_id" : 860187,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In my case there was a mismatch between the build path JRE and installed JRE on execution environment. I moved into Project > Properties > Java compiler. There was a warning message at the bottom.</p>\n\n<p>I clicked on the links 'Installed JRE', 'Execution environment', 'Java build path' and changed the JDK version to 1.7 and the warning disappeared.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2120900,
      "reputation" : 16064,
      "user_id" : 1884158,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 87,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/b36Zh.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "modulitos",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1884158/modulitos"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 10,
    "last_activity_date" : 1424660167,
    "last_edit_date" : 1495535499,
    "creation_date" : 1401594068,
    "answer_id" : 23976565,
    "question_id" : 860187,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In addition to <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/2174607/1494802\">Nels Beckman's solution</a>, I have the following tips:</p>\n\n<p>Under <em>Configure Build Path</em>, I had to rearrange the order of my entries under <em>Order and Export</em>.</p>\n\n<p>Additionally, as an Eclipse PDE developer, I needed to rearrange the order of my dependencies in my <code>MANIFEST.MF</code>, adding the problematic package as first on the list.</p>\n\n<p>Playing with these dials, along with running <em>Project > Clean</em> in between, I was able to resolve these warnings.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3370312,
      "reputation" : 1759,
      "user_id" : 2829676,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 43,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b61ea982d8ecd304ad83a6bb7ead5cb8?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Samitha Chathuranga",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2829676/samitha-chathuranga"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1406566625,
    "creation_date" : 1406566625,
    "answer_id" : 25000302,
    "question_id" : 860187,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Just change the order of build path libraries of your project. Right click on project>Build Path> Configure Build Path>Select Order and Export(Tab)>Change the order of the entries. I hope moving the \"JRE System library\" to the bottom will work. It worked so for me. Easy and simple....!!!</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3779583,
      "reputation" : 1401,
      "user_id" : 3139451,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/73bjr.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Vijay Bhatt",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3139451/vijay-bhatt"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 6,
    "last_activity_date" : 1424087516,
    "creation_date" : 1424087516,
    "answer_id" : 28540843,
    "question_id" : 860187,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Go to the Java Build Path in the project properties. Remove the existing JRE System Library \nThen Add it again i.e. Add Library-->JRE Lib--select jre--->Finish.\nLastly select <strong>order and export</strong> tab select JRE Lib and move on top. That's it.</p>\n"
  }, {
